{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_hamlet_ver01/data/sn84025909/00542865301/1957112801/0471.xml":{"full_text":"Page 4 ST. PAUL SUN Thursday, November 28, 1957\nTwin City Observer Sun Publishing Co., Inc.\nST. PAUL SUN\nINDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED MAY 7, 1941\nPublished every Thursday at St. Paul, Minnesota, by the\nTwin City Observer St. Paul Sun Publishing Co., Inc-\nMinneapolis Phone FE 9-3271 St. Paul Phone CA 5-8825\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES $2.00 Per Year. Six Months $1.25\nAll Mail Subscriptions Payable in Advance\nEditorial and Business Offices at 858 Iglehart Ave., St. Paul, Minnesota\nMILTON G. WILLIAMS\nESTYR BRADLEY PEAKE\nROBERT A. JONES\nEntered as second class matter October 11, 1951 at the post office at\nSt. Paul 1, Minnesota, under the act of March 3, 1879.\n-flcnv e\nMember: National Editorial Association, Minnesota Editorial\nAssociation, National Newspaper Publishers Association\nEDITORIAL....\nTHE IMPORTANCE OF THE INDIVIDUAL, in this period\nwhen it is the unthinking fashion to echo the sentiment that,\n\u201cno one is indispensable,\u201d was emphasized in dramatic manner\nearly this week when President Eisenhower was stricken.\nApparently there is reason to believe, as well as hope,\nthat the setback to his health was of minor importance, and\nthat recovery will be speedy as well as complete, and for that\nall Americans are grateful. Their prayers may help speed his\nrecovery.\nBut the point is the news of the President\u2019s affliction\ncreated a sensation throughout the civilized world. Here is\njust one man out of countless millions but what happens,\nor could happen to him, can well shape the destiny of the en\ntire world.\nThe President of the United States, no matter who holds\nthe office, is a figure of world importance one of the most\nimportant men in the world. And because one man can be\nso important, by virtue of the office he holds, we should be\nmade a little more aware of the importance of every individ\nual, whether his station in life be exalted or humble.\nSuch awareness helps, too, to recognize the basic falsity\nof the philosophy that, \u201cthe individual is not important.\u201d That\nsimply is not true. Almost every individual is important\nto someone.\nON THE STATE POLITICAL SCENE, one of the most\nimportant developments in many months is the reaching of\nagreement between Roy Dunn, former Minnesota Republican\nnational committeeman, and John Hartle, state Republican\nchairman, and other officials of the party\nIt is unfortunate that there ever was the kind of breach\nthat temporarily isolated Mr Dunn, but that\u2019s all ancient his\ntory now.\nThe important point is that once again, Roy Dunn\u2019s po\nlitical wisdom and experience, his good judgment and ener\ngetic leadership will be available to the state GOP.\nThe full extent to which he and his counsel have been\nmissed is easy to measure. Just take a look at the victorious\nDFL officeholders, the Liberal-Labor control of the lower House\nof the Legislature, and the black prospects for the 1958 cam\npaign.\nNow, though, GOP chances of victory are much better,\nwith Roy Dunn back in a position of party leadership.\nTHE BITTER TRUTH of what discrimination can mean\nhas been emphasized to a great many people in recent years\nbut this is not the kind of discrimination that is so familiar to\nmembers of minority groups.\nThis kind of discrimination, as a matter of fact, is di\nrected against the majority of people although only a rela\ntive few are affected by it.\nThe discrimination in question is job discrimination\nbecause of age. Race, color or creed has nothing to do with it.\nIt is the apparently growing practice of many large firms to\nrefuse to hire any job applicants over the age of forty.\nThe reasons for this kind of discrimination are most often\nvague, quite often contradictory, very seldom valid. Actually,\nit would be difficult for anyone to give a really good reason\nfor a blanket refusal to hire skilled, mature, responsible work\ners just because they have reached the age of forty, which\nisn\u2019t even regarded as being middle-aged.\nThis kind of discrimination will bring dismay to those\nwho already are the victims of enough varieties without being\nsubjected to discrimination because of age, too.\nEditor Publisher\nSt. Paul Representative Columnist\nAdvertising Manager\ncantorians\n(Continued from Page 1)\nval. The Cantorians next ap\npearance will be in concert at\nthe Red Wing, Minnesota, aud\nitorium on December 12, 1957.\nThis will be a requested return\nengagement because of an out\nstanding performance given by\nthe group previously. All per\nsons interested in applying for\nmembership please contact:\nMiss Earline Neil, Secretary,\nCA. 5-4729, or Mr. Bradford\nBenner, Pres., CA. 7-2859.\nThe Cantorians were organ\nized in St. Paul four years ago\nby Mr. Alexander Jordan.\nU OF M STUDENTS..\n(Continued from Page One)\nUniversity of Minnesota school\nbooks and thumbed through\na couple of them. He then said,\n\u2018That\u2019s what\u2019s the matter with\nyou niggers, now, getting too\neducated.\u2019\nIn his statement Cox said\n\u201cAbout this time another\npatrol car came up and a fel\nlow he called Bill came over.\nHe said to me, \u201chow come you\ndon\u2019t talk like these cotton\npicking niggers down here?\u201d I\nreplied, \u2018I was raised in Min\nnesota\u2019 and he said, \u2018you know\nyou left Mississippi and went\nnorth and brought this yellow\nDryers were invented\nA for MOTHERS\nW WA\u00ae\n1/ V Donahoe\nLi j* Northern States Power Company\u2019s\nZ V ft* 46 Horne Service Consultants\nWhen youngster* come in with wet snow suits, Baby'* stuffed toys dry soft and Diapers come out of a dryer soft\nyou can get their suits dry, the children back out cuddly (after washing) in your and fluffy, never harsh and stiff,\nto play in no time. Brush off snow and loose dirt, electric dryer. Be sure seams are And they smell clean, fresh and\nClose zippers or fasteners. Tumble suits in your sewed tightly and all breakable sweet. Never a trace of musty\nelectric dryer until dry. Handy! And a dryer trim removed. Toys may be \u201cbasementodor\u201d \u2014nevera touch\nsaves lugging three tons of wet clothes a year. dried together, if colorfast. of the soot from clotheslines.\nEnjoy your back yard; don\u2019t work in To\u00bb\u00ab clothes from washer to Did you know it takes an average of 625\nit. Your old clothesline poles will dryer, set a dial\u2014and that\u2019s all. steps to hang out a single basket of clothes?\nmake fine, sturdy props for swings Your dryer does the work quiet- It takes only 3 with an electric dryer. And\nwhen you start drying clothes with ly, automatically; you go about you\u2019ll never think about \u201cdrying weather\u201d\nan electric dryer. By actual time other household tasks. You\u2019ll again. A dryer does a beautiful job winter or\nstudies, a dryer saves three hours of wonder why you put off getting summer \u2014it actually dries better than the\nhard work a week. a dryer so long. sun! Clothes get fluffier, too.\nTake the work out of washday... with an\nElectric Clothes Dryer\nSee your appliance dealer or Northern States Power Company\nnigger back down here so you\ncan show him how you live\ndown here.\u2019 One patrolman then\nwalked by and said, \u2018why don\u2019t\none of you niggers try to take\nmy gun so I can give both of\nyou a free trip up north in a\nbox, then you won\u2019t have to\npay this fine you are going to\nget when the sheriff comes, he\nmight even throw in some flow-\ners.\u2019\nWhen the sheriff arrived he\nfined the young men $25 for\ncarry concealed weapons and\n$33.52 for speeding 8.5 miles per\nhour, although Cox claims he\nwas not exceeding the speed\nlimit of 50 to 60 miles per hour.\nNeither of the young men made\nany objections to the charges.\n\u201cIf it hadn\u2019t been for the\nsheriff I think they (the pa\ntrolmen) might have shot us\nright there,\u201d Moffatt said. Cox\nsaid they were kept standing\nin the cold during the entire\nincident, from about 8:20 until\n10:00 P.M., before being allow\ned to drive away.\nSome of the language alleg\nedly used by the officers, as\ndescribed in the almost identi\ncal statements to the NAACP\nbranch, was unprintable. Frank\nM. Smith, branch president, re\nleased the report to the press.\nNEW APPOINTEES\n(Continued from Page 1)\nMrs. Shirley Ann Hickman is\na junior clerk.\nA native of Beckley, West\nVirginia, Miss Rinehart was\neducated in that city and came\nto St. Paul in 1951. She was\nformerly employed as a nurses\naide at Gillette Hospital and\nalso worked in war industry.\nThe new assistant cashier says\nshe likes her position and finds\nher co-workers \u201cwonderful.\u201d\nMrs. Hickman, 873 Iglehart\nAve., is a graduate of St. Paul\nCentral High School. She is the\nwife of the well known photog\nrapher, Maurice Hickman, and\nthe couple have two children,\n3 year old Cynthia, and 2 year\nold Patricia. Mrs. Hickman is\na member of Mt. Olivet Baptist\nChurch.\nIn speaking of the new ap\npointees Mr. Rosen said their\nemployment was based solely\non their \u201cexcellent qualifica\ntions\u201d and that the department\nwill continue to practice a fair\nemployment policy on the basis\nof ability, without regard for\nrace, color, creed or national\norigin.\n\u201cA lot of people might spend\nless time watching TV if only\nthey could remember what i t\nwas they used to do.\u201d\u2014Charles\nRuffing.","height":"21666","width":"15174"}}
